ncluded him on its list of the hundred most influential individuals of the twentieth century. Before finding his calling as a politician, however, Harvey variously tried being a schoolteacher, a securities analyst on Wall Street, a supporter of Barry Goldwater, a Broadway theater assistant, a bead-wearing hippie, the operator of a camera store and organizer of the local business community in San Francisco. He rejected Judaism as a religion, but he was deeply influenced by the cultural values of his Jewish upbringing and his understanding of anti-Semitism and the Holocaust. His early influences and his many personal and professional experiences finally came together when he decided to run for elective office as the forceful champion of gays, racial minorities, women, working people, the disabled, and senior citizens. In his last five years, he focused all of his tremendous energy on becoming a successful public figure with a distinct political voice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aGay liberation movementzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 0aGay menzCaliforniazSan FranciscovBiography. 0aGay politicianszCaliforniazSan FranciscovBiography. 0aJewish menzCaliforniazSan FranciscovBiography. 0aPoliticianszCaliforniazSan FranciscovBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2018z978311063899840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300235272423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300235272.jpg  a978-3-11-063899-8  YUP eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles